			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I don't understand this:
<br />

<br />
"You can only be resurrected if you haven't released and are still lying on the ground dead."
<br />

<br />
Released? So you die and you just lie there hoping for a res and if you don't get one you "release" and run back?
<br />

<br />

<br />
The whole thing makes me want to just solo, or if I do group, use a /disband hotkey right before some idiot gets dead. If I was a puller, I'd definately make a "DISBAND NOW I'M GONNA DIE!" hotkey right next to my "Incoming %t" hotkey. 
<br />

<br />
Also, what if the casters gate? If they are in a different zone, will they take the penalty? Or, if you are running back to your shard and someone else dies, you still get a penalty if your in another zone?
<br />

<br />
And what about those people that go LD a lot, they'll NEVER get a group. "LFG- 45 Assassin - Cable modem"
<br />

<br />
As a scout, able to "evac" a group, I can say that for sure, if anyone in my group even gets <span style="font-style: italic">low</span> on health I'm evaccing. There's no way I'm taking an exp loss for someone that can't play.
<br />

<br />
Unless you are in a raid environment and doing new content, you shouldn't be dying anyhow. Hell, friends and I often went weeks without dying except in raids. 
<br />

<br />
Plus, it will make people a LOT less likely to group with strangers. If they are not in your guild (hell, even then sometimes) why risk grouping with an unknown factor? 
<br />

<br />
The old way, if someone was a bad player, you just booted them from the group. I see a lot more arguing and blaming group members with this shared exp thing.
<br />

<br />
 I know I'm the eternal pessimist, but I just don't like this system.</span><!-- SIG HERE --><span class="postbody"><div style="width: 400; height: 155; overflow: hidden;"><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://server5.uploadit.org/files/Forestknight-Xerosig.jpg" border="0" /></div</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
